title: Office of Personnel: The Position Management and Compensation Division, 1946-1967

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Office of Personnel: The Position Management and Compensation Division, 1946-1967
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

A copy of the historical study Office of Personnel: The Position Management and Compensation Division, 1946-1967.

I am a member of the news media and request classification as such. I have previously written about the government and its activities, with some reaching over 100,000 readers in outlets such as MuckRock, Motherboard, Property of the People, AND Magazine, Unicorn Riot, and more. As such, as I have a reasonable expectation of publication and my editorial and writing skills are well established. In addition, I discuss and comment on the files online and make them available through non-profits such as the library Internet Archive and and the journalist non-profit, MuckRock, disseminating them to a large audience. While my research is not limited to this, a great deal of it, including this, focuses on the activities and attitudes of the government itself. As such, it is not necessary for me to demonstrate the relevance of this particular subject in advance.

Additionally, case law states that “proof of the ability to disseminate the released information to a broad cross- section of the public is not required.” Judicial Watch, Inc. v. Dep’t of Justice, 365 F.3d 1108, 1126 (D.C. Cir. 2004); see Carney v. U.S. Dep’t of Justice, 19 F.3d 807, 814-15 (2d Cir. 1994). Further, courts have held that "qualified because it also had “firm” plans to “publish a number of . . . ‘document sets’” concerning United States foreign and national security policy." Under this criteria, as well, I qualify as a member of the news media.

Additionally, courts have held that the news media status "focuses on the nature of the requester, not its request. The provision requires that the request be “made by” a representative of the news media. Id. § 552(a)(4)(A)(ii)(II). A newspaper reporter, for example, is a representative of the news media regardless of how much interest there is in the story for which he or she is requesting information." As such, the details of the request itself are moot for the purposes of determining the appropriate fee category.

As my primary purpose is to inform about government activities by reporting on it and making the raw data available, I request that fees be waived.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Emma Best
An acknowledgement letter, stating the request is being processed.

communications.subject: RE: Oklahoma Open Records Act Request #OCPD-3750-2025
communications.communication:
To whom it may concern: 
I am writing to formally appeal the denial of my request for records under the Oklahoma Open Records Act (“ORA”), which I submitted on 3/26/25. I respectfully request a written explanation detailing the specific grounds for the denial, including the precise subsections of the ORA that are being relied upon.
According to the ORA, “all records of public bodies and public officials shall be open to any person for inspection, copying, or mechanical reproduction during regular business hours…” unless specifically exempted by law. Your response cited the Oklahoma Open Records Act generally, referring to Sections 2, 5, 8, 14, and 20, but did not indicate what specific subsections within those provisions justify withholding the records I requested.
To ensure that the denial complies with the legal requirements of the ORA, and to allow me to properly evaluate the legitimacy of the denial, I ask that you provide the following:
The specific subsection(s) within ORA Sections 2, 5, 8, 14, and/or 20 that are being relied upon.


1. A description of how those subsections apply to the records I requested.


2. A list or description of the categories of records being withheld in whole or in part.


3. Whether any portion of the requested records is non-exempt and therefore subject to partial disclosure with redactions, as required by Oklahoma law.


The law is clear: ORA emphasizes transparency and access to public records as a matter of public policy. The Act requires that denials be specific and justified under the law; vague or categorical denials are inconsistent with both the letter and spirit of the Act.
I respectfully request a response to this appeal within a reasonable timeframe, ideally within seven (7) business days of receipt, so that I may determine my next steps.
If you require any clarification regarding my original request or this appeal, please let me know promptly.
Thank you.

communications.subject: Re: RE: Oklahoma Open Records Act Request #OCPD-3750-2025
communications.communication:
Good Day, 
  
 RE: OCPD-3750-2025 / 2004-0051703 
  
 Per the Municipal Counselors Office on Apr. 2, 2025 @ 06:25 AM: "2004-0051703 provide open record version of incident report 000 and arrest report 013. Otherwise denied; ORA Sections 8 and 14." 
  
 After being unsure that your materials had been mailed out, I mailed out another copy of your materials on 05/27/2025. 
  
 In order to file an appeal: 
  
 The process is defined in Section 8 of the Open Records Act Law Enforcement Agency Records Available for Public Inspection, a link provided on the JustFOIA web page under “Open Records.” 
  
 Otherwise, the original decision was made by the Municipal Counselors Office. They can be contacted at 405-297-3830. Contact name is Orval Jones. Please provide your request number, OCPD-3750-2025, when you call so that they can reference your request. 
  
 Thank you.

communications.subject: RE: Oklahoma Open Records Act Request #OCPD-4095-2025
communications.communication:
To whom it may concern: 
I am writing to formally appeal the denial of my request for records under the Oklahoma Open Records Act (“ORA”), which I submitted on 3/26/25. I respectfully request a written explanation detailing the specific grounds for the denial, including the precise subsections of the ORA that are being relied upon.
According to the ORA, “all records of public bodies and public officials shall be open to any person for inspection, copying, or mechanical reproduction during regular business hours…” unless specifically exempted by law. Your response cited the Oklahoma Open Records Act generally, referring to Sections 2, 5, 8, 14, and 20, but did not indicate what specific subsections within those provisions justify withholding the records I requested.
To ensure that the denial complies with the legal requirements of the ORA, and to allow me to properly evaluate the legitimacy of the denial, I ask that you provide the following:
The specific subsection(s) within ORA Sections 2, 5, 8, 14, and/or 20 that are being relied upon.


1. A description of how those subsections apply to the records I requested.


2. A list or description of the categories of records being withheld in whole or in part.


3. Whether any portion of the requested records is non-exempt and therefore subject to partial disclosure with redactions, as required by Oklahoma law.


The law is clear: ORA emphasizes transparency and access to public records as a matter of public policy. The Act requires that denials be specific and justified under the law; vague or categorical denials are inconsistent with both the letter and spirit of the Act.
I respectfully request a response to this appeal within a reasonable timeframe, ideally within seven (7) business days of receipt, so that I may determine my next steps.
If you require any clarification regarding my original request or this appeal, please let me know promptly.
Thank you.

Upload documents directly: https://accounts.muckrock.com/accounts/login/?next=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.muckrock.com%2Faccounts%2Flogin%2F%3Fnext%3D%252Faccounts%252Fagency_login%252Fsanta-monica-police-department-371%252Ffield-interview-cards-santa-monica-police-department-185562%252F%253Femail%253DVirginia.Connolly%252540smgov.net&url_auth_token=AAAdKEUUTzoD2yyBeUP-jjU-owY%3A1u9amk%3AJIjCgJWgXxtnGToV4fy_XznItus73fryfo3zwOMMST4" We have withheld records that contain sensitive intelligent and security procedure information because the public interest in non-disclosure exceeds the public interest in disclosure for the reasons discussed below. (Gov. Code § 7922.000.) The public interest must be weighed whether such disclosure “would contribute significantly to public understanding of government activities” and serve the legislative purpose of ‘‘shed[ding] light on an agency's performance of its statutory duties.’’ ( City of San Jose v. Superior Court (1999) 74 Cal.App.4th 1008, 1019.) Here, disclosure of this record would not significantly contribute to an understanding of the City’s performance or duties. Moreover, the release of this information could result in the misuse of documents intended for sensitive public safety incidences.  For these reasons, in weighing the public interest, the City finds that the public interest served by nondisclosure of these types of records outweighs the public interest served by disclosure. 
Sincerely, 
Doberne #3797 
Police Records Supervisor 
Santa Monica Police Records

communications.subject: Re: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: 1998-1999 New Utrecht High School Yearbook Records
communications.communication:
Hi Sarah.

Thanks for your inquiry. The Library does have a series of yearbooks which are free for the public to review. Alas, we do not have the 1998-1999 New Utrecht High School Yearbook in our collection.

You can learn more about the collection here: https://findingaids.library.nyu.edu/cbh/bcms_0031/

And you can learn about all of the resources at the Center for Brooklyn History here: https://www.bklynlibrary.org/cbh/collections/collections-resources

Let us know if you need anything else? Many thanks.

Fritzi Bodenheimer | Press Officer
Brooklyn Public Library

title: Flock Safety search audits, network sharing, and general order (College Place Police Department)

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Flock Safety search audits, network sharing, and general order (College Place Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records related to the department’s Flock Safety system:
1. Organization Audit in Flock. 
The report should include data logged from the period of December 1, 2024, to the date this request is processed. Per Flock's documentation, the Organization Audit is available within the Insights tab and is defined as searches done within the agency.

2. Network Audit in Flock.
The report should include data logged from the period of December 1, 2024, to the date this request is processed. Per Flock's documentation, the Network Audit is available within the Insights tab and is defined as searches of the organization’s Flock network by any agency in the Flock System.

3. A list of network share settings that include:
3a. Flock networks shared with me
3b. Networks that I’m sharing

Please provide records in their original electronic, machine readable format. For example, please provide csv or spreadsheet files where applicable. Please do not redirect me to your transparency portal.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Rose Terse

title: Deaths-in-custody data

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Deaths-in-custody data
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

(1) Records, or an in index of records, of all California law enforcement agencies deaths-in-custody between 1980 and today’s date, including all deaths-in-custody reported pursuant to California Government Code (GC) section 12525.

(2) Records, or an index of records, of any and all California law enforcement agencies’ responses to the California Department of Justice annual survey of the total number of subject deaths per calendar year since 1980 or since the state began gathering such data, including pursuant to California Government Code (GC) section 12525.

I understand that the California Department of Justice maintains part of this data online, including on the Open Justice portal, however, this request is seeking data in a downloadable, .csv-readable format dating back to 1980 or since the state began gathering such data, whichever is greater.

If records pursuant to this request are possessed in machine-readable format such as an .xls or .csv spreadsheet file, please provide the record in this format.

The fundamental rule of the CPRA is a presumption of public access. “In other words, [A]ll public records are subject to disclosure unless the Legislature has expressly provided to the contrary.” Williams v. Superior Court, 5 Cal. 4th 337 (1993). This presumption finds further support in the California Constitution, as amended by Proposition 59 in 2004. “A statute, court rule, or other authority, including those in effect on the effective date of this subdivision, shall be broadly construed if it furthers the people's right of access, and narrowly construed if it limits the right of access.” Cal. Const. Art. 1 § 3(b)(2).

Please provide a determination on this request within 10 days of your receipt of it. If you determine that any or all of the information qualifies for an exemption from disclosure, please note whether, as is normally the case, the exemption is discretionary, and if so whether it is necessary in this case to exercise your discretion to withhold the information. If you determine that some but not all of the information is exempt from disclosure and that you intend to withhold it, please redact it for the time being and make the rest available as requested. In any event, please provide a signed notification citing the legal authorities on which you rely if you determine that any or all of the information is exempt and will not be disclosed.

Please apply a fee waiver to this request. If the request for a fee waiver is denied, please provide notification of any duplication costs exceeding $80 before you duplicate the records. If the request for a fee waiver is denied, please further provide an index of all other requests since 2014 for which a fee waiver was denied, and the reason therefor.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Dillon Bergin

title: Washington Public Records Act Request: Personnel and Conduct Records (Jefferson County Sheriff's Office)

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Washington Public Records Act Request: Personnel and Conduct Records (Jefferson County Sheriff's Office)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the State of Washington Public Records Act, Chapter 42.56 RCW, I respectfully request copies of the following records covering the past ten (10) years:

Employee Information:
•	Personnel Rosters: Full list of current and former officers and staff, including names, badge numbers, 
ranks/positions, assignments, hiring dates, lengths of service, and current salaries.
•	Separated Personnel Records: Officer names, badge numbers, ranks/positions, dates of separation, reasons for separation, and any disciplinary or investigation findings related to separated employees.
•	Internal Affairs Complaints Logs: Logs of complaints filed against officers, including dates, nature of complaints, investigation summaries, and outcomes.
•	Demographic Breakdown of Staff: Information regarding race, gender, age, and years of service for all personnel.
•	Disciplinary Records: Records of sustained misconduct, reprimands, suspensions, demotions, and terminations.
•	Citizen Complaint Records: Complaints filed by members of the public, including investigation records and findings.
•	Officer Training Records: Records of completed certifications, dates of training courses, and ongoing education.
•	Use of Force Reports: Reports and records detailing any incidents where physical force was used, including the type of force (firearms, tasers, batons, etc.).
•	Officer-Involved Shooting Reports: Investigative files and administrative reviews regarding officer-involved shootings.
•	Early Intervention System (EIS) Data: Records identifying officers flagged for multiple complaints, use of force incidents, or other concerning behavior.
•	Performance Evaluations: Annual or biannual performance reviews for individual officers.
•	Grievance Records: Labor grievances filed by or against officers.
•	Supervisor Notes and Counseling Records: Informal disciplinary notes and performance counseling documentation.
•	Resignation and Retirement Records: Records detailing reasons for resignations or retirements, especially after critical incidents.
•	Awards and Commendations: Records of any awards, commendations, or honors given to officers.
•	Off-Duty Misconduct Records: Records involving arrests or disciplinary actions related to off-duty behavior.
•	Records of Lawsuits Against Officers: Civil suits alleging officer misconduct, civil rights violations, or other professional conduct matters.
•	Settlement Agreements Involving Officers: Terms and details of any settlement agreements, including any non-disclosure clauses.
•	Brady Lists: Lists or notifications identifying officers with documented credibility issues.
•	Body-Worn Camera Misuse or Policy Violation Records: Instances where officers failed to comply with body-worn camera policies.
•	Records of Transfers and Reassignments: Records regarding officer transfers or reassignments, including reasons where available.
•	Fitness-for-Duty Evaluations: Psychological or medical evaluations required after misconduct allegations or other triggering events.
•	Promotions and Demotions Records: Application materials, evaluation records, and decision memorandums regarding promotions and demotions.
•	Employment Application Materials: Initial applications, resumes, background check summaries (redacted for private information if necessary).
•	Secondary Employment Approvals: Records showing agency approval for secondary employment by officers (e.g., security jobs).
•	Internal Memos Regarding Conduct Policy Changes: Memos or correspondence discussing changes to conduct policies, disciplinary procedures, or related codes.
•	Salary Records: Current and historical salary data for all personnel, including base pay, overtime, special assignment pay, and bonuses.

Format and Fees:
In order of preference, I would prefer that this data be provided as: plain text with comma-separated-values (CSV file), OpenDocument spreadsheet, Excel spreadsheet, or the native electronic format of the software from which this information is retrieved in fulfillment of my request. I specifically request that you not create a new record by rendering to PDF or by printing your electronic record then scanning it to make a series of images of the printed data.

Please produce the records in electronic format (.csv, .xlsx, .ods, etc.) via email or secure download link to avoid unnecessary copying costs.

If the total estimated cost to fulfill this request exceeds $25, please provide a written, itemized cost estimate before proceeding. Pursuant to RCW 42.56.120(2)(b), I request a waiver or reduction of fees as this request is made for the purpose of public interest and community oversight, not for commercial purposes.

If Portions Are Exempt:
If any portions of the requested records are exempt from disclosure, please provide a written explanation for each redaction or withheld record, citing the specific exemption relied upon.

If Delayed or Denied:
If fulfillment of this request will take longer than the statutory time frame, or if you believe any aspect is overly burdensome, please provide a written explanation identifying specifically which portions are burdensome and propose a timeline for rolling production of records as they become available.

Thank you for your prompt attention to this request. Please feel free to contact me at [Insert Your Email] if clarification is needed.

Sincerely,

Aurora Quinn

communications.communication:
--- Please respond above this line --- 
RE: PUBLIC RECORDS REQUEST of April 29, 2025, Reference # S003598-042925 Dear Aurora  Quinn, The County received the following public records request from you on April 29, 2025: To Whom It May Concern: 

Pursuant to the State of Washington Public Records Act, Chapter 42.56 RCW, I respectfully request copies of the following records covering the past ten (10) years: 

Employee Information: 
• Personnel Rosters: Full list of current and former officers and staff, including names, badge numbers, 
ranks/positions, assignments, hiring dates, lengths of service, and current salaries. 
• Separated Personnel Records: Officer names, badge numbers, ranks/positions, dates of separation, reasons for separation, and any disciplinary or investigation findings related to separated employees. 
• Internal Affairs Complaints Logs: Logs of complaints filed against officers, including dates, nature of complaints, investigation summaries, and outcomes. 
• Demographic Breakdown of Staff: Information regarding race, gender, age, and years of service for all personnel. 
• Disciplinary Records: Records of sustained misconduct, reprimands, suspensions, demotions, and terminations. 
• Citizen Complaint Records: Complaints filed by members of the public, including investigation records and findings. 
• Officer Training Records: Records of completed certifications, dates of training courses, and ongoing education. 
• Use of Force Reports: Reports and records detailing any incidents where physical force was used, including the type of force (firearms, tasers, batons, etc.). 
• Officer-Involved Shooting Reports: Investigative files and administrative reviews regarding officer-involved shootings. 
• Early Intervention System (EIS) Data: Records identifying officers flagged for multiple complaints, use of force incidents, or other concerning behavior. 
• Performance Evaluations: Annual or biannual performance reviews for individual officers. 
• Grievance Records: Labor grievances filed by or against officers. 
• Supervisor Notes and Counseling Records: Informal disciplinary notes and performance counseling documentation. 
• Resignation and Retirement Records: Records detailing reasons for resignations or retirements, especially after critical incidents. 
• Awards and Commendations: Records of any awards, commendations, or honors given to officers. 
• Off-Duty Misconduct Records: Records involving arrests or disciplinary actions related to off-duty behavior. 
• Records of Lawsuits Against Officers: Civil suits alleging officer misconduct, civil rights violations, or other professional conduct matters. 
• Settlement Agreements Involving Officers: Terms and details of any settlement agreements, including any non-disclosure clauses. 
• Brady Lists: Lists or notifications identifying officers with documented credibility issues. 
• Body-Worn Camera Misuse or Policy Violation Records: Instances where officers failed to comply with body-worn camera policies. 
• Records of Transfers and Reassignments: Records regarding officer transfers or reassignments, including reasons where available. 
• Fitness-for-Duty Evaluations: Psychological or medical evaluations required after misconduct allegations or other triggering events. 
• Promotions and Demotions Records: Application materials, evaluation records, and decision memorandums regarding promotions and demotions. 
• Employment Application Materials: Initial applications, resumes, background check summaries (redacted for private information if necessary). 
• Secondary Employment Approvals: Records showing agency approval for secondary employment by officers (e.g., security jobs). 
• Internal Memos Regarding Conduct Policy Changes: Memos or correspondence discussing changes to conduct policies, disciplinary procedures, or related codes. 
• Salary Records: Current and historical salary data for all personnel, including base pay, overtime, special assignment pay, and bonuses. 

Format and Fees: 
In order of preference, I would prefer that this data be provided as: plain text with comma-separated-values (CSV file), OpenDocument spreadsheet, Excel spreadsheet, or the native electronic format of the software from which this information is retrieved in fulfillment of my request. I specifically request that you not create a new record by rendering to PDF or by printing your electronic record then scanning it to make a series of images of the printed data. 

Please produce the records in electronic format (.csv, .xlsx, .ods, etc.) via email or secure download link to avoid unnecessary copying costs. 

If the total estimated cost to fulfill this request exceeds $25, please provide a written, itemized cost estimate before proceeding. Pursuant to RCW 42.56.120(2)(b), I request a waiver or reduction of fees as this request is made for the purpose of public interest and community oversight, not for commercial purposes. 

If Portions Are Exempt: 
If any portions of the requested records are exempt from disclosure, please provide a written explanation for each redaction or withheld record, citing the specific exemption relied upon. 

If Delayed or Denied: 
If fulfillment of this request will take longer than the statutory time frame, or if you believe any aspect is overly burdensome, please provide a written explanation identifying specifically which portions are burdensome and propose a timeline for rolling production of records as they become available. 

Thank you for your prompt attention to this request. Please feel free to contact me at [Insert Your Email] if clarification is needed. 

Sincerely, 

Aurora Quinn 

Upload documents directly: https://accounts.muckrock.com/accounts/login/?next=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.muckrock.com%2Faccounts%2Flogin%2F%3Fnext%3D%252Faccounts%252Fagency_login%252Fjefferson-county-sheriffs-office-35220%252Fwashington-public-records-act-request-personnel-and-conduct-records-jefferson-county-sheriffs-office-185736%252F%253Femail%253Djnole%252540co.jefferson.wa.us&url_auth_token=AAGleWFczW3cyV5iQFlhuFOS7Jc%3A1u9x90%3AKCxjEj5LjwQO1vxW4KL6XvlE_tuWhH_Cl1xA8skaZTU 
Due to the extensive amount of information requested some additional time will be needed to locate, compile and review responsive records. We estimate that public records responsive to this request will be available within 60___ business days from today, on or before 8/1/2025. If public records become available in advance of this estimate we will contact you promptly. Conversely, if the County encounters a need to extend our estimate, we will contact you promptly with a revised estimated date. Thank you for your patience in awaiting this information. Sincerely, Lynn Chesterfield 
Support Services Technician 2 
Sheriff's Office 
Jefferson County 
360-385-3831

communications.subject: RE: Washington Public Records Act Request #S003598-042925
communications.communication:
Subject: Request for Clarification Regarding Records Request Timeline

Dear Lynn Chesterfield,

Thank you for your response to my public records request.

I respectfully express concern regarding the 60-business-day estimate provided. A comparable request submitted recently to another regional law enforcement agency was processed with a significantly shorter timeline and a projected fulfillment date of May 27, 2025. This suggests that the records I’ve requested— which are routinely maintained by public agencies— may be reasonably accessible without requiring such an extended delay.

I understand that some of the materials may require review or redaction. However, under RCW 42.56.520, agencies are required to provide the “reasonable estimate” of time necessary to produce records, and I respectfully ask for more detail as to what is contributing to this 60-business-day estimate.

If possible, I also request that responsive records be released on a rolling basis as they become available, rather than in a single, delayed release. I am open to narrowing or prioritizing specific sections of my request to assist in timely fulfillment.

Thank you again for your time and attention. I look forward to your response and hope to work collaboratively to ensure the timely release of these important public records.

Sincerely,

Aurora Quinn

21. Records of Transfers and Reassignments: Records regarding officer transfers or reassignments, including reasons where available. 
22. Fitness-for-Duty Evaluations: Psychological or medical evaluations required after misconduct allegations or other triggering events. 
23. Promotions and Demotions Records: Application materials, evaluation records, and decision memorandums regarding promotions and demotions. 
24. Employment Application Materials: Initial applications, resumes, background check summaries (redacted for private information if necessary). 
25. Secondary Employment Approvals: Records showing agency approval for secondary employment by officers (e.g., security jobs). 
26. Internal Memos Regarding Conduct Policy Changes: Memos or correspondence discussing changes to conduct policies, disciplinary procedures, or related codes. 
27. Salary Records: Current and historical salary data for all personnel, including base pay, overtime, special assignment pay, and bonuses. 
I will be coordinating your records request with the Jefferson County Sheriff's Office (JCSO). My apologies for the very long estimate that was initially sent to you. I was out of town and one of the records staff at JCSO sent that estimate based on their perception of the size of your request. We do actually intend to produce records by installment as records are located, compiled and review is completed. A few of your request items are relatively simple and can correspondingly be produced relatively quickly. However, unless I'm misunderstanding any details, the overall scope of your request appears to be massive. I have taken the liberty of numbering each of the bulleted items in your request, for ease of reference. I would guess that 27 of your requests, taken together, comprise a significant portion, probably a majority, of all of JCSO's administrative records. Many of the requested records will require detailed review and redaction which is a time-consuming process. Some of the requested records will also require third party notice to be sent to subjects of the records, which will also add to the overall processing time for those records. Given limitations in personnel and the need to prevent excessive interference with other essential operations, it will take a period of many months to complete all 27 items of your request. But, as I mentioned, we will produce records by installment as they are compiled, prepared and reviewed. Some of the records you are requesting exist in paper files only. The county charges 10 cents a page for scans of paper records, so there will be some charges for certain installments along the way. The total cost of all charges will almost certainly be well in excess of $25. Each time we anticipate charges for a certain installment, we will first send you an estimate of the charges, showing an estimate of the number of pages to be scanned. We estimate that public records responsive to this request will be available within nine business days from today, on or before 5/30/2025. If public records become available in advance of this estimate we will contact you promptly. Conversely, if the County encounters a need to extend our estimate, we will contact you promptly with a revised estimated date. Thank you for your patience in awaiting this information. Sincerely, Ken Hugoniot 
Public Records Administrator 
Central Services 
Jefferson County 
360-385-9174

communications.subject: RE: Washington Public Records Act Request #S003598-042925
communications.communication:
Dear Mr. Hugoniot,

Thank you for your detailed explanation regarding the scope and complexity of my public records request. I appreciate your transparency about the challenges involved, including the time required for review, redaction, and third-party notifications, as well as the potential costs associated with scanning paper records.
Understanding the broad nature of my request, I want to be mindful of limiting costs and minimizing any operational burden on Jefferson County. To that end, I would be happy to work with you to identify an initial set of 10–15 high-priority categories that can be compiled and released earlier in the process. If you could advise which of the requested items are more readily accessible or less resource-intensive to produce, that would help me focus the request accordingly. Additionally, I would appreciate it if you could provide a simple tracking update or log indicating the current status of each category as they move through review and preparation. This would help me monitor progress and plan accordingly.

Thank you again for your willingness to produce records on a rolling basis and for providing advance estimates of any anticipated charges. I look forward to receiving the first installment of records by May 30, 2025, or sooner if available, and to working collaboratively toward a transparent and timely resolution.

Sincerely,

Aurora Quinn

communications.communication:
--- Please respond above this line --- 

Hello Aurora, 
We have reviewed each of the items in your request and identified a few items which can be completed expeditiously. We have also identified some other items for which we have either no responsive records or very few responsive records. Unless you have any objection, we will process those requests first and then move on to larger and more time-consuming requests. The items we identified for this "first round" are numbers 
1, 3, 4, 10, 12, 13, 16, 17, 19, and 20. 
You asked for something like a tracking update or log to track the progress of each item.  The best way to approach this is to create a new request in our public records request system for each item when we begin working on it. These will be essentially sub-requests. The sub-requests will give both you and us an easy way to track the progress of each item. All of the records produced for an item will be stored in that item's sub-request and provided via the sub-request. Also all communication regarding each item, including time estimates for providing installments of records can also be conducted via the corresponding sub-request. All of the sub-requests will appear as individual requests in your account and each of them will have its own reference number that gets generated when it's entered. I'll be creating a few of these sub-requests today and you'll get an automatic acknowledgement email from each one as it's created. 
Please let me know if you have any questions or objections about any of this. 
Thank you, Ken Hugoniot

1820 Jefferson St. 
Port Townsend, WA 98368

Subject: Refining Scope of Records Requests Before Proceeding

Dear Mr. Hugoniot,

Thank you for your earlier responses regarding my records requests. Before proceeding with payment or next steps, I would like to take time to refine the scope of the requested records to ensure clarity and reduce unnecessary time and cost for both parties.

I am currently reviewing the following 27 requested items and will be preparing a refined, tiered list identifying:
•	Which items apply to current employees only vs. former employees (and how many years back, e.g., last 3–10 years),
•	Which apply specifically to sworn officers vs. administrative staff,
•	Which categories should be prioritized first for delivery.

I also acknowledge that you have already provided:
•	The personnel roster of current employees (Item #1) via the Muckrock portal,
•	A formal response indicating no responsive records for Item #10 (Early Intervention System Data),
•	A formal response indicating no responsive records for Item #20 (Body-Worn Camera Misuse or Policy Violations).

While I reserve the right to revisit these items or seek administrative appeal later, if necessary, I will focus for now on refining the scope of the remaining requests. Please also note that I intend to process all communications and records delivery solely through the Muckrock portal to keep everything centralized. Once I finalize and submit the refined list, I will follow up regarding payment arrangements and next steps.

Thank you for your cooperation. I’ll be back in touch with you shortly.

Sincerely,

Aurora Quinn

communications.subject: RE: Washington Public Records Act Request #S003639-052225
communications.communication:
Subject: Refined Public Records Request – Tier 1 Items (Clarification and Follow-Up)

Dear Mr. Hugoniot,

Thank you again for your responses to my previous public records request. As part of the clarification and refinement process, I am writing to follow up only on the Tier 1 items that were identified for refinement. These items include: 1, 3, 4, 10, 12, 13, 16, 17, 19, and 20. My goal is to clarify these requests so they can be processed in a manner consistent with Jefferson County’s records practices and Washington’s Public Records Act. Additionally, I want to clarify that I am not using my personal email address for correspondence. All communications should continue through the MuckRock portal, where this request is being formally tracked.

Please see my refined requests below:

Item 1 – Personnel Rosters (Refined Request)
I received a spreadsheet labeled:
•	Personnel_Roster.Current_Employees
However, this request has not been fully fulfilled because:
•	Hire dates are missing for all current employees.
•	Official position descriptions are missing for all listed positions.
Please provide:
1.	The hire date for each individual listed in the current employee roster (this field is currently blank).
2.	The official position description for each unique rank/position title listed (e.g., Patrol Sergeant, Corrections Officer, Support Services Tech I/II, Animal Control Officer, etc.).
Position descriptions may be provided in the format used by Jefferson County Human Resources for job classifications or duty statements.

Item 3 – Internal Affairs Complaints Logs (Refined Request)
Please provide logs or records of complaints filed against sworn officers from January 1, 2015 to the present, including:
•	Date of complaint
•	Name(s) of officer(s) involved
•	Badge number(s)
•	Nature/type of complaint
•	Summary of allegations
•	Status and outcome
•	Date investigation closed
•	Disciplinary action taken (if any)
This applies to both current and former sworn officers employed during the time period. Records may be provided in spreadsheet or narrative form; whichever format includes all the above fields.

Item 4 – Demographic Breakdown of Staff (Refined Request)
Please provide a demographic breakdown of all current employees of the Jefferson County Sheriff’s Office, including:
•	Race/ethnicity
•	Gender
•	Age or age range
•	Rank/position title
Years of service may be included optionally. A summary table or anonymized dataset is acceptable if required for privacy.

Item 10 – Early Intervention System (EIS) Data (Clarification Request)
You stated there are no responsive records and that this is the “final, definitive response.”
To clarify, I am requesting:
1.	Whether Jefferson County Sheriff’s Office has ever maintained an Early Intervention System (EIS) or similar mechanism for identifying concerning officer behavior.
2.	Whether any policies, communications, or evaluations exist relating to EIS or comparable oversight systems.
3.	Confirmation that no such system or record has existed during the past 10 years, if applicable.
4.	A description of the search process used to determine no responsive records exist.

Item 12 – Grievance Records (Refined Request)
Please provide formal grievance records filed by or against current or former sworn personnel in the past 10 years, including:
•	Date of grievance
•	Nature of grievance
•	Names or job titles of parties involved
•	Investigation summaries (if available)
•	Final outcomes
A summary log is acceptable, but please include any related documents if maintained.

Item 13 – Supervisor Notes and Counseling Records (Refined Request)
Please provide supervisor notes or informal counseling records for current and former sworn personnel from the past 10 years, including:
•	Informal warnings
•	Supervisor memos or notes
•	Performance improvement plans (PIPs) not tied to formal discipline
•	Coaching documentation
If these records are not systematically maintained, please indicate so.

Item 16 – Off-Duty Misconduct Records (Refined Request)
Please provide records from the past 10 years involving off-duty misconduct by current or former sworn personnel, including:
•	Incident reports
•	Internal/external investigation documentation
•	Arrests, citations, or disciplinary findings
This includes off-duty conduct that triggered internal review or formal findings.

Item 17 – Records of Lawsuits Against Officers (Refined Request)
Please provide records of any lawsuits filed in the past 10 years involving current or former sworn personnel, including:
•	Officer names (if available)
•	Case summaries and allegations
•	Court docket numbers or identifiers
•	Final outcomes (settled, dismissed, adjudicated)
•	Any internal documentation tied to the case
If full case files are extensive, an index or summary table with references is sufficient.

Item 19 – Brady/Giglio List Records (Refined Request)
Please provide records from the past 10 years identifying current or former sworn personnel who:
•	Were flagged for credibility concerns
•	Were placed on a Brady or Giglio list
•	Were subject to notifications involving dishonesty or bias
This includes:
•	Notices to/from prosecutors
•	Internal documentation or summaries
•	Any determinations related to Brady/Giglio obligations
If the Sheriff’s Office does not maintain a Brady list internally, please confirm whether any correspondence or determinations exist from the Prosecutor’s Office.

Item 20 – Body-Worn Camera Misuse or Policy Violations (Refined Request)
You stated that there are no responsive records and that there have been no violations since the body-worn camera program began in 2022.
To ensure clarity and accountability, please provide:
1.	Any records of complaints, investigations, or disciplinary actions regarding body-worn camera misuse since 2022.
2.	Documentation of the search process used to confirm no records exist, including:
•	The staff members involved in the search
•	The methods and date(s) of the search
•	Any applicable policies related to BWC misuse
If no responsive records truly exist, that is understood, but I am requesting verification of the basis for the determination.

Please confirm receipt of this refined request and feel free to contact me via the MuckRock portal if you require clarification. Thank you for your time and assistance.

Sincerely,

Aurora Quinn

communications.subject: RE: Washington Public Records Act Request #S003639-052225
communications.communication:
Subject: Public Records Request — Refined Tier 2 and Tier 3 Items

Dear Mr. Hugoniot,

Thank you again for your assistance with my ongoing public records request. Following up on our prior communications, please find below the refined requests for Tier 2 and Tier 3 items. These refinements are intended to clarify exactly which records I am seeking, to help ensure the requests can be processed efficiently and in accordance with Jefferson County’s records practices and Washington’s Public Records Act.

Please note the following important points:
•	Some records may require third-party review or employee sign-off, which could delay processing.
•	You are welcome to release records as they become available or to reorder and prioritize the tiering as needed.
•	To help keep costs low and avoid unnecessary charges, please provide an itemized estimate of fees before incurring any costs.

Please see my refined requests below:

Tier 2 — Refined Requests

Item 5 – Disciplinary Records
Please provide records of any sustained misconduct findings for current and former sworn officers, including reprimands, suspensions, demotions, and terminations, with documentation of the nature of misconduct and disciplinary decisions.

Item 6 – Citizen Complaint Records
Please provide complaints filed by the public against sworn officers from January 1, 2015, to present, including investigation records, findings, and any resulting disciplinary actions. Applies to current and former sworn officers.

Item 7 – Officer Training Records
Please provide detailed training records for all current sworn officers, including certifications, course names, completion dates, and ongoing or refresher education.

Item 8 – Use of Force Reports
Please provide all reports documenting use of force incidents by sworn officers from January 1, 2015, to present, including type of force, dates, officer names and badge numbers, and circumstances. Includes current and former sworn officers.

Item 9 – Officer-Involved Shooting Reports
Please provide investigative files and administrative reviews related to officer-involved shootings, including internal and external investigations and outcomes, for current and former sworn officers.

Item 11 – Performance Evaluations
Please provide performance evaluations for current and former sworn officers, including narrative comments, ratings, and recommendations.

Item 14 – Resignation and Retirement Records
Please provide records detailing reasons for resignations or retirements of sworn officers, especially related to critical incidents or disciplinary matters, including dates and accompanying documentation.

Item 15 – Awards and Commendations
Please provide records of awards, commendations, or honors given to sworn officers, including dates, types, and reasons for recognition.

Tier 3 — Refined Requests

Item 18 – Settlement Agreements Involving Officers
Please provide full terms and details of settlement agreements involving sworn officers, including any confidentiality or non-disclosure provisions.

Item 21 – Records of Transfers and Reassignments
Please provide records regarding transfers or reassignments of sworn officers, including reasons and effective dates, for current and former sworn officers.

Item 22 – Fitness-for-Duty Evaluations
Please provide psychological or medical evaluation records conducted as fitness-for-duty assessments triggered by misconduct or other events for sworn officers.

Item 23 – Promotions and Demotions Records
Please provide application materials, evaluation records, and decision memorandums related to promotions and demotions of sworn officers, including dates and justifications.

Item 24 – Employment Application Materials
Please provide initial employment applications, resumes, and background check summaries for sworn officers only, redacted as necessary for privacy.

Item 25 – Secondary Employment Approvals
Please provide records showing agency approval for secondary employment by sworn officers, including application dates and approval status.

Item 26 – Internal Memos Regarding Conduct Policy Changes
Please provide memos or correspondence discussing changes to conduct policies, disciplinary procedures, or codes of conduct.

Item 27 – Salary Records
Please provide current and historical salary data for sworn officers, including base pay, overtime, special assignment pay, and bonuses.

Please confirm receipt of this refined request. I appreciate your time and assistance. Feel free to contact me through the MuckRock portal if you require clarification.

Sincerely,

Aurora Quinn

Please provide investigative files and administrative reviews of officer-involved shootings for current/former sworn officers.

Item 11 – Performance Evaluations
Please provide performance evaluations for current and former sworn officers, including comments, ratings, recommendations.

Item 14 – Resignation and Retirement Records
Please provide records detailing reasons for resignations or retirements of sworn officers, especially related to critical incidents.

Item 15 – Awards and Commendations
Please provide records of awards or honors given to sworn officers, including dates, types, reasons.


Tier 3 – Refined Requests

Item 18 – Settlement Agreements Involving Officers
Please provide terms and details of settlements involving sworn officers, including confidentiality provisions.

Item 21 – Records of Transfers and Reassignments
Please provide records of transfers or reassignments of sworn officers, including reasons and effective dates.

Item 22 – Fitness-for-Duty Evaluations
Please provide fitness-for-duty evaluation records for sworn officers.

Item 23 – Promotions and Demotions Records
Please provide application materials, evaluations, decision memos related to promotions/demotions, dates, justifications.

Item 24 – Employment Application Materials
Please provide initial employment applications, resumes, background summaries for sworn officers.

Item 25 – Secondary Employment Approvals
Please provide records showing agency approval for secondary employment by sworn officers.

Item 26 – Internal Memos Regarding Conduct Policy Changes
Please provide memos or correspondence about changes to conduct policies or disciplinary procedures.

Item 27 – Salary Records
Please provide current and historical salary data for sworn officers, including base pay, overtime, bonuses.


Thank you for your time and assistance. Please confirm receipt of this refined request through this MuckRock portal, and let me know if further clarification is needed.

Sincerely,

Aurora Quinn

communications.communication:

The Excel spreadsheet version is the previously-used version which is no longer kept up to date, but it contains some information that is not included in the current list. communications.subject: FOIA Case No. 2025-FPRO-02594
communications.communication:
This responds to your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request dated June 5, 2025, in which you seek access to Postal Service records. Specifically, your request states:



Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:



* Any current USPS training module, training material or handout for delivery workers concerning bear encounters and bear attacks, and

* The most-recent yearly report describing numbers of attacks on postal workers by wind and/or stray animals that mentions bears, and

* The previous year's edition of that report.



Attached please find a stand-up safety talk regarding bear safety. This talk is available for our field management to use whenever needed.



As to the second and third item in your request, a search was conducted that reveals that there are no records available responsive to your inquiry. The United States Postal Service does not track accidents and/or injuries by specific animal. A keyword search for the word "bear" did not reveal any incidents.



If you are not satisfied with the response to this request, you may file an administrative appeal within ninety (90) days of the date of this response letter by writing to the General Counsel, U.S. Postal Service, 475 L'Enfant Plaza, SW, Washington, DC 20260 or via email at FOIAAppeal@usps.gov. Your appeal must be postmarked or electronically transmitted within ninety (90) days of the date of the response to your request.



The letter of appeal should include, as applicable:

(1) A copy of the request, of any notification of denial or other action, and of any other related correspondence;

(2) The FOIA tracking number assigned to the request;

(3) A statement of the action, or failure to act, from which the appeal is taken;

(4) A statement identifying the specific redactions to responsive records that the requester is challenging;

(5) A statement of the relief sought; and

(6) A statement of the reasons why the requester believes the action or failure to act is erroneous.



For further assistance and to discuss any aspect of your request, you may contact FOIA Public Liaison listed below:

PRIVACY & RECORDS OFFICE US POSTAL SERVICE 475 L'ENFANT PLAZA SW RM 1P830 WASHINGTON DC 20260-1101 Phone: (202) 268-2608 Fax: (202) 268-5353 Email: FOIA12@usps.gov

FOIA Public Liaison: Nancy Chavannes

Additionally, you may contact the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) at the National Archives and Records Administration to inquire about the FOIA mediation services they offer. The contact information for OGIS is as follows: Office of Government Information Services, National Archives and Records Administration, 8601 Adelphi Road-OGIS, College Park, Maryland 20740-6001, e-mail at ogis@nara.gov; telephone at 202-741-5770; toll free at 1-877-684-6448; or facsimile at 202-741-5769.

Linda DeCarlo | Sr. Director - Occupational Safety & Health
United States Postal Service | 475 L'Enfant Plaza, SW | Washington, DC  20260
O - (202) 268-3587 | M - (202) 360-9339

title: South Carolina Medical Board

communications.subject: South Carolina Public Records Law Request: South Carolina Medical Board
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the South Carolina Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

I’m conducting national research on how medical boards across the U.S. manage physician mental health and substance use cases—especially in relation to physician health or monitoring programs. A key question is whether such programs operate independently or in concert with disciplinary enforcement.

I respectfully request the following records from the South Carolina Board of Medical Examiners (or LLR) for the period 2019–2024:

1. A list of disciplinary actions involving physicians where:

Psychological or psychiatric impairment was cited

Substance use or behavioral health concerns were involved

2. Board or departmental policies or procedures regarding:

Referrals to the South Carolina Recovering Professional Program (RPP)

Evaluation of return-to-practice after monitoring or treatment

3. Agreements, contracts, or memoranda of understanding between the board and RPP, including:

Confidentiality provisions

Reporting requirements

Criteria for board acceptance or rejection of RPP recommendations

4. Summary statistics or internal reports showing:

Number of referrals to RPP

Voluntary vs. mandated participation

Return-to-practice outcomes

Any cases where the board diverged from RPP recommendations

5. Evaluations or audits (internal or external) assessing RPP’s independence or effectiveness.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Vig Sinclair

title: Fremont PD Dismissed Red Light Camera Tickets [2020-2025]

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Fremont PD Dismissed Red Light Camera Tickets [2020-2025]
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records relating to the number of red light camera tickets that were dismissed by the officer reviewing the footage/photograph captured by the camera starting from January 2020 to December 2025.

The information requested is readily available for extraction through the Redflex System. For example, a records request for similar data fulfilled by the Beverly Hills Police Department of Beverly Hills, CA provided a Customer Management Report generated by the Redflex System. That provided Customer Management Report is attached to this request for reference.

However, should you disagree, you may alternatively produce the following records:

* Number of Potential Violations collected by the Redflex System between the periods of January 2020 to December 2025, preferably segregated by year or month

* Number of Authorized Violations collected by the Redflex System between the periods of January 2020 to December 2025. This may also be the number of Electronic Signatures given by the Authorized Officer using the Redflex

* Monthly reports generated by the Redflex Standard Report System, as mentioned in Section 7.8.2 of the AGREEMENT BETWEEN THE CITY OF FREMONT AND REDFLEX TRAFFIC SYSTEMS, INC. FOR PHOTO RED LIGHT ENFORCEMENT PROGRAM (a copy of this agreement is attached to this request for reference)

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

John Doe

title: Superintendent Travel

communications.subject: Virginia Freedom of Information Act Request: Superintendent Travel
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Virginia Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

A publicly available VMI Alumni Association publication, "Turnouts", released this week, states that Maj. Gen. Wins received several commendations from them. A trip by the Superintendent to the Republic of China was also mentioned. Therefore, I am requesting:

1. Copies of the commendations, awards, etc., given by the Alumni Agencies and their organizations to Maj. Gen. Wins in his capacity as VMI Superintendent. These are now public documents.

2. Records showing the itinerary, meetings, or other events, agenda, travel, results, and all related information for the Superintendent's trip to the Republic of China, as well as the source of funds to pay for the trip.  The publication stated that he went in his official capacity as Superintendent of VMI and conducted VMI or Joint VMI and Alumni Agencies business, so these records are subject to FOIA, as he is a public employee.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Tom Nash, a citizen of Virginia, in coordination with Anonymous.

communications.subject: RE: Virginia Freedom of Information Act Request: Superintendent Travel
communications.communication: I also want to add to my FOIA records showing anyone who travelled with the Superintendent to the Republic of China, VMI employee or not, their role, itinerary, etc., and the source of funding for their travel.

title: VMI Admissions Data

communications.subject: Virginia Freedom of Information Act Request: VMI Admissions Data
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Virginia Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records for the following academic years showing:

1. The breakout of applicants accepted for admission to VMI (appointments) by race, ethnicity, gender, and within each of those, which were athletes and non-athletes

2. The breakout of new cadets that matriculated to VMI (showed up and enrolled on admissions day) by race, ethnicity, gender, and within each of those, which were athletes and non-athletes.

3. The number and dollar value of each scholarship or tuition assistance from cadets by race, ethnicity, gender, and within each of those, which were athletes and non-athletes, with the source of funding (e.g., VMI Agencies, Federal Government, VMI internal funds, other).

Academic years covered:

2015 - 2016
2016 - 2017
2017 - 2018
2018 - 2019
2019 - 2020
2020 - 2021
2021 - 2022
2022 - 2023
2023 - 2024
2024 - 2025

This information is known to be a reporting requirement for various state and federal agencies, and, in the past, some, if not all, was available in the VMI Data Dashboard that has since been closed. Therefore, this information should be readily available in that,a dn tother readily available systems and systems of systems to be provided.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Tom Nash, a citizen of Virginia, in coordination with Anonymous.

communications.subject: [OpenRecords] Request FOIL-2025-841-00078 Closed
communications.communication:
The Department of Transportation (DOT) has closed your FOIL request FOIL-2025-841-00078 for the following reasons: (https://a860-openrecords.nyc.gov/request/view/FOIL-2025-841-00078) 
 Your request under the Freedom of Information Law (FOIL) has been reviewed and the documents you requested have been posted on the OpenRecords portal. 
Please check your email inbox's spam folder to ensure you received all records provided by the agency.

title: Police department misconduct allegations and disciplinary proceedings

communications.subject: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: Police department misconduct allegations and disciplinary proceedings
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records:

All materials and records describing and sufficient to show/disclose all allegations of misconduct made and all disciplinary proceedings taken against any officer, employee, or representative of this policing agency. 

As described in the New York Freedom of Information Law, a record is "any information kept, held, filed, produced or reproduced by, with or for an agency or the state legislature, in any physical form whatsoever including, but not limited to, reports, statements, examinations, memoranda, opinions, folders, files, books, manuals, pamphlets, forms, papers, designs, drawings, maps, photos, letters, microfilms, computer tapes or discs, rules, regulations or codes." Records kept in a digital or electronic form are also records, would be responsive to this request, and should be provided. 

These records are typically required to be retained under the New York State Records Retention and Disposition Schedule MU-1 (http://www.archives.nysed.gov/records/retention_mu-1), including, but not limited to, item no. 365, which includes: "Investigative records and disciplinary proceedings, including but not limited to statement of charge, transcript of hearing, notice of decision, letter of termination or resignation, letter of reinstatement, record of appeal procedure, and correspondence." While materials under that schedule have a set retention of 3 years after the final decision rendered, this request and materials responsive to it include *all* records held in the possession of any office or individual employed or formerly employed by this policing agency, including those kept off-site, in digital form, and in personnel files. 

Please note that any failure to provide all potentially-responsive materials and/or the destruction of materials potentially responsive to this request would be a violation of the spirit of the New York Freedom of Information Law, as well as unlawful under the New York FOIL and the terms of the attached litigation hold notice.

Materials responsive to this request include — but are not limited to — all complaints, reports, records of discipline and penalties, aggregate collections of complaint and disciplinary materials (spreadsheets, databases), investigatory materials, relevant related correspondence, photographs, video, other related evidence, proof of discipline or fulfillment of penalties, and all personnel materials (including those used in promotion, contract, and other employment negotiations and considerations) that reference or utilize misconduct allegations or disciplinary materials of any sort.

Materials responsive to this request include all complaints— internal, external, and civilian — and include records disclosing the names, badge numbers, and personnel identification of each officer involved and/or serving as a witness, as well as all available details of the incident/complaint: date, time, location, nature of the incident, description of the incident, nature of the investigation, investigatory materials, the disposition of the case, and any subsequent materials related to the execution of any resultant discipline. Responsive materials include all complaints and allegations against any officer, employee, or representative of this policing agency, regardless of whether that complaint or allegation resulted in any investigation or disciplinary action. 

Responsive materials also include all records of use of force by officers, including records disclosing the names, badge numbers, and personnel identification of each officer involved and/or serving as a witness, as well as all available details of the incident: date, time, location, nature of the incident, description of the incident, nature of the use of force, subsequent investigatory materials related to the use of force, the disposition of any investigation into the incident, and any subsequent materials related to the use of force. 

Please provide materials on a rolling basis, beginning with materials created during the following timeframes: 
• January 1, 2010 - June 15, 2020
• January 1, 2000 - January 1, 2010
• January 1, 1990 - January 1, 2000
• January 1, 1980 - January 1, 1990
• January 1, 1970 - January 1, 1980

Pursuant to NYCRR Section 1401.5(c)(1), should any of this request be unclear or lack sufficient description for your office, please provide direction that would enable this requester to request records reasonably described. Please also note that the New York FOIL states: "An agency shall not deny a request on the basis that the request is voluminous or that locating or reviewing the requested records or providing the requested copies is burdensome because the agency lacks sufficient staffing or on any other basis if the agency may engage an outside professional service to provide copying, programming or other services required to provide the copy...." Please also see FOIL AO 19671, an Advisory Opinion from the Committee on Open Government [https://docs.dos.ny.gov/coog/ftext/f19671.htm]. 

If your office has questions about this request or would like to discuss it for any reason, please contact this requester via the contact email address provided and feel free to follow up by phone: 617-299-1832. This request is being submitted to each policing agency in New York as part of a collaborative project led by MuckRock and involving multiple other educational and journalistic partners and participants. For this reason, over the lifetime of this request, your agency may interface with individuals not listed on this initial communication. 

This request is being made in the public interest by a news organization as part of non-profit (not commercial) journalistic work and research on behalf of the public. In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request and as part of the necessary negotiations for successful processing. As far as it is possible, please fulfill elements of this request electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter.

I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Beryl Lipton

communications.subject: RE: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: Police department misconduct allegations and disciplinary proceedings
communications.communication:
Hello, Ms. Jones —

I received your email responding to a phone call placed to your office by Hayden Kim to follow up on a FOIL request we submitted in June 2020. 

I have attached the acknowledgement letter sent by your office in April 2021. I would not like to resubmit this request, as we have been patiently waiting for a response for multiple years. I understand that it might take additional weeks to respond to the request at this point, but I would appreciate knowing when your office anticipates being able to release a first batch of records.

Please let me know if you have any questions or would like to discuss this further.

Thank you very much for your time and help. 

Best wishes,
Beryl

communications.subject: Re: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: Police department misconduct allegations and disciplinary proceedings
communications.communication:
Good afternoon,
We have finally completed the request and downloaded the scanned files to a
disc.  The cost of the disc is $5.00 plus postage totaling *$5.64*.
Unfortunately, we don't have the capabilities to accept payment for FOIL
requests over the phone or website, so it will have to be via check or
money order.  Once we receive payment, I will send the disc in the mail.
Check can be made payable to "City of Fulton" and mailed to 141 S. First St.

                      Fulton, NY 13069
Please reference "Muck Rock FOIL" in the memo line.

Let me know if you have any questions.


Regards,
*Cassandra Jones*
Sr. Account Clerk
City of Fulton Police Department
Phone: 315-598-4504 ext. 3
www.fultonpd.com

title: David Kahl Interrogation

communications.subject: Wisconsin Open Records Act Request: David Kahl Interrogation
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Wisconsin Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I would like to request for the interrogation video of  David Kahl, who was interviewed by the  Madison Police Department.
Additionally, I also ask for  Brittany Zimmermann' crime scene reports from April 2, 2008.
and any recordings of 911 calls that are accessible.
as well as any additional case-related investigative materials and photos. Thanks Mahad

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Mahad Mohammed

communications.subject: Re: Thank you for contacting City of Madison Police Records
communications.communication:
Your email request has been received and placed in our processing queue.  Due to the volume of requests, the estimated processing time is as follows:

.         Standard records request (reports/video/photos)- approximately 6-8 weeks

·         Contacts, calls for service or background checks- 2 weeks.


You will be contacted when your request has been completed.

If you are requesting a crash report, these are maintained at the Department of Transportation.  They can be contacted  directly at https://app.wi.gov/crashreports or by calling (608) 266-8753 (and selecting option 3).  For processing this request, you will need the DOT document number located in the upper right corner of the Driver Exchange of Information Form.  This document number will begin with 9B or 01L.  Crash reports are available from DOT approximately 2 weeks after the date of the crash.

If you need any further information, please visit our website at www.cityofmadison.com/police/services<http://www.cityofmadison.com/police/services> or call (608) 266-4075 between 8:00 a.m. and 4:00 p.m. Monday through Friday.  Thank you for contacting Madison Police Records.

communications.subject: Welcome to the Public Request Center!
communications.communication:
Dear Mahad Mohammed, 
 
Welcome! Thank you for registering with the City of Madison Public Records Request Center. 
 
Your Login ID is:  182299-95330491@requests.muckrock.com 
 
The Public Records Request Center allows you to: 
 
  * Track and monitor the status of your request 
  * Message the Records Custodian processing your request 
  * Pay online for any fees assessed 
  * Receive any relevant documents

communications.subject: INVOICE - Madison Police Department Records Request :: P003801-031825
communications.communication:
RE: Madison Police Department Records Request of March 02, 2025, Reference # 31P003801-031825. 
Dear Mahad Mohammed, 
Your invoice is ready, and available to view. Payment is due within 30 days of the date of the invoice. Payment is required before releasing relevant records. 
Payment options include: 
Online payment:  login to your City of Madison Public Records Request Center account and select View My Invoices. 
You can also pay in-person or by mail at: 
Madison Police Department 
Attn: Police Records 
211 S. Carroll St 
Suite #GR10 
Madison, WI 53703 
 Include the bottom portion of the invoice with your payment. 
 
Sincerely, 
Madison Police Records 
 You must disable your devices pop-up blocker to view your files.  See below for Apple/Android directions. Apple mobile devices default to pop-up blocker ON. To change your settings on your device: Settings-> Apps-> Safari-> Block Pop-ups-> The toggle switch needs to be OFF After making this change, return to the link and attempt to download the document again. Your Apple device will default to opening the item in iBooks unless otherwise specified on your device. Android mobile devices do not have a default pop up blocker but the default browser, Chrome, has a built-in pop-up blocker ON. To turn off the pop-up blocker in Chrome on Android: Open Chrome-> Tap the three dots (more) in the top right corner of the browser-> Settings-> Site Settings- > Pop-ups and redirects-> The toggle switch to allow pop-ups

title: Public Records Request - Bedford

communications.subject: Indiana Access to Public Records Act Request: Public Records Request - Bedford
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Indiana Access to Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am writing to formally request access to video footage from a police intervention, specifically from the body camera worn by the officer(s) and the dashcam of the police vehicles involved. Article: https://www.wbiw.com/2025/01/06/bedford-man-arrested-after-disorderly-behavior-and-resisting-arrest-at-local-restaurant/ 

Exact date of incident: December 19, 2024 Names of parties involved: John J. Werner Location: Mammas and Pappas, a local restaurant, Bedford
 
I intend to use this footage solely for educational purposes to promote a better understanding of law enforcement procedures and the application of the law. I understand that there may be associated costs for providing this footage, and I am more than willing to cover any fees incurred. Please inform me about the necessary procedures and the costs involved. Thank you in advance for your assistance. I trust that this footage will be invaluable for my educational efforts, and I greatly appreciate your cooperation. Best regards, George Smith

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 7 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

George Smith
